        new TestedOpcode(0x0027, "INVENTORY_MOVE",
            "Opcodes/SectorInventoryMoveTests.cs InventoryMove_UnrecognisedFromInv_ReceivesUnrecognisedErrorString — client sends a canonical 24-byte InvMove payload {int32 GameID=0; int32 FromInv=99; int32 FromSlot=0; int32 ToInv=0; int32 ToSlot=0; int32 Num=0} BIG-ENDIAN on the sector connection after STAGE handshake completes. The handler at server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:2474 ntohl-decodes every field (wire is network byte order, NOT host-LE like Wave 26's SkillUse) then switches on InvMo.FromInv. FromInv=99 is outside every populated case (1=Cargo, 2=Equip, 3=Vault, 4=Buy, 6=Loot, 12=ManuOverride, 14=ManuResult, 16=Trade, 18=LootConfirm) and falls into the default arm at PlayerConnection.cpp:3238 which calls SendVaMessage(\"UNRECOGNISED INVENTORY MOVE!\\nPlease submit a bug report\\n\"). SendVaMessage → SendMessageString → SendOpcode(0x001D) — per-client UDP queue, no SendToSector login-stage race. Test asserts the reply body contains the literal substring \"UNRECOGNISED INVENTORY MOVE\". Catches: (a) PacketStructures.h InvMove long-revert regression (currently 6× int32_t = 24B canonical; if any field is widened to `long` on Linux x86_64 the struct grows and FromInv reads from the wrong offset — would likely still hit the default arm because most populated cases are 1-18 and a shifted read of zeros stays in default, but a struct reshuffle that landed FromInv on a populated value would silently mutate inventory); (b) ntohl/htonl byte-order flip on FromInv (a missing ntohl would read 99 BE as 1660944384 host-LE — still in default arm, latent false negative documented in xmldoc but worth flagging); (c) dispatcher mis-route at server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:455 (case label sits immediately before 0x0029 ITEM_STATE — a copy-paste swap with HandleItemState would mis-interpret the 24B InvMove as an 11B ItemState, reading Inventory==2 mutation branch with garbage offsets); (d) proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping the opcode (0x0027 is not explicitly listed