d similarly over-read. The survival-probe REQUEST_TIME path catches the survive-vs-crash boundary; a future byte-comparison wave would tighten further. (d) **Proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping 0x005D.** 0x005D is not explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp's ProcessSectorServerOpcode switch (verified by grep — no 005D/EQUIP_USE references in proxy/), so it falls through to the bottom-of-switch default ForwardClientOpcode arm at line 514-517. A regression dropping that default arm would mean the server never sees the EQUIP_USE frame — the test would still pass via the REQUEST_TIME path's explicit forwarding (REQUEST_TIME goes through the same default arm, so a true default-arm drop would also break REQUEST_TIME — the test would time out, surfacing the regression). (e) **Equipable::ManualActivate early-return ordering at Equipable.cpp:551.** The current guard is `if ((m_AuxEquipItem == NULL) || (m_AuxEquipItem->GetData() == NULL) || (m_AuxEquipItem->GetItemTemplateID() < 0)) return;`. Reordering the short-circuit (e.g. checking GetItemTemplateID() before the NULL pointer check) on a slot where m_AuxEquipItem happened to be NULL would dereference NULL. For our test case slot 15 is guaranteed non-NULL but the guard reorder regression is real-world possible. (f) **The Equipable.m_AuxEquipItem→Inventory.EquipInv.EquipItem[SlotNum] alias at Equipable.cpp:61.** Setting m_AuxEquipItem to point at the parent ship's inventory entry is the canonical lifetime contract — a refactor that re-points m_AuxEquipItem to a local stack address or transient copy would still satisfy the NULL check (the pointer is non-NULL) but the item's data view would be stale. Test doesn't directly assert this (would need to populate the slot and check item-state changes propagate) but documents the contract. (g) **SendOpcode header-width revert at PlayerConnection.cpp:127.** Phase K sizeof(int32_t) opcode-header fix keeps the per-client UDP queue header at 4B; a revert corrupts the 0x2016 inner-tuple parser → REQUEST_TIME survival probe silent. Same shape as Waves 11/27/29/30/36/37/38/39/40/41. (h) **Proxy SendClientPacketSequence inner-opcode guard tightening at UDPProxyToClient_linux.cpp:568.** Currently passes 0x0034 CLIENT_SET_TIME because 0x0034 < 0x0FFF (this is the same proxy guard that BLOCKS 0x2011 GALAXY_MAP_CACHE for the unrelated 0x0098 dispatch — see Wave 42 triage in plans/00-master.md). Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: 0x005D EQUIP_USE is what the retail Win32 client emits when the user clicks the \"use\" button on an inventory slot in the ship UI. Sending it for an empty slot is a legal client behaviour (the slot might be empty from the user's perspective due to lag or UI staleness); the retail server's empty-slot no-op is exactly preserved. Zero permissiveness added; not loosening any security posture; not fabricating any reply."),
